<table border="0" width="570">
  <tr>
    <td><p align="center"><font size="2"><b>THE CHIROPRACTIC EDUCATION AND PRACTICE IN THE USA</b></font></p>
    <p align="center"><font size="2">Medhat M.Alattar</font></p>
    <p align="center"><font size="2">Life University School of Chiropractic,<br>
    USA</font></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 40; text-align: justify"><font size="2">The profession of chiropractic originated in Davenport,
    Iowa in 1895, when Daniel David Palmer formulated the theory of the spinal subluxation,
    and pioneered the process of adjusting the spine to correct nerve interference caused by
    misaligned vertebrae. </font></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 40; text-align: justify"><font size="2">Chiropractic is the large non-invasive health care
    profession in the world and is the third of all health care professions ranking
    immediately after medicine and dentistry.</font></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 40; text-align: justify"><font size="2">According to the council on Chiropractic education
    &quot;the application of science in Chiropractic concerns itself with the relationship
    between structure, promarily the spine, and function, promarily coordinated by the nervous
    sytem of the human body as that relationship affects the restortion and preservation of
    health. Further, this application of science in chiropractic focuses on the inherent
    ability of the body to heal without the use of drugs or surgery&quot;.</font></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 40; text-align: justify"><font size="2">Chiropractic is concerned with adjustment the spine to
    free it from subluxations. Subluxation is defined as &quot;any alterations of the
    biomechanical and physiological dynamics of contiguous spinal structures which cause
    neurological disturbances&quot;. An adjustment is a chiropractic procedure done by hand to
    correct a misaligned vertebrae.</font></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 40; text-align: justify"><font size="2">In education, the council on chiropractic Education is
    the officially recognized chiropractic accrediting agency from the U.S.Department of
    Education. There are 16 accredited Chiropractic Colleges in the USA with a total
    enrollment of about 14,000 students. The typical chiropractic curriculum covers abour 5112
    hours of instructions including about 888 hours of clinical chiropractic training. To be
    admitted to Chiropractic college candidate must have a minimum of two years of
    pre-professional college education with a curriculum concentrated in basic and biological
    sciences, the chiropractic degree program includes four years of resident instruction at a
    chiropractic cillege.</font></td>
  </tr>
</table>
